WEBVTT

00:01.435 --> 00:02.033
<i> Previously on "diggstown".</i>

00:02.069 --> 00:03.535
Oh, I'm getting this.

00:04.739 --> 00:05.937
Avery:
<i> Marcie, I'm sick of this.</i>

00:05.973 --> 00:07.906
<i> Everything is about you</i>

00:08.042 --> 00:10.709
And I'm choking on
your narcissism!

00:10.844 --> 00:11.777
Get out.

00:11.846 --> 00:13.311
Avery:
<i> Iris.</i>

00:14.615 --> 00:18.450
Ezra elvins will toss you
under a bus like that.

00:18.585 --> 00:19.551
Vivian:
<i> Absolutely certain.</i>

00:19.620 --> 00:21.186
<i> I don't wanna be</i>
<i> where I'm not wanted.</i>

00:21.188 --> 00:22.287
Marcie:
<i> She's giving me thirty days</i>

00:22.323 --> 00:23.888
To pay back the eight million
that she invested.

00:23.924 --> 00:25.858
Trudy:
<i> He was supposed to meet</i>
<i> me yesterday morning,</i>

00:25.993 --> 00:27.793
But he never showed.

00:27.795 --> 00:28.727
According to the police,

00:28.796 --> 00:30.529
Mr. Allen was
drinking on the boat.

00:30.664 --> 00:32.897
Ellery:
<i> No water in his lungs,</i>
<i> so he didn't drown.</i>

00:32.933 --> 00:34.666
He died on that boat and
was thrown overboard.

00:34.668 --> 00:36.134
Marcie:
<i> We are gonna find out</i>

00:36.203 --> 00:38.169
<i> Exactly what happened to him.</i>

00:39.373 --> 00:40.205
[thwack]
[groans]

00:40.274 --> 00:41.807
Mike macleod:
<i> Wake your ass up!</i>

00:41.876 --> 00:48.814
[suspenseful music]

00:48.883 --> 00:49.948
♪

00:49.984 --> 00:51.015
What is this?

00:51.052 --> 00:52.283
Mike macleod:
<i> Hope you don't get seasick.</i>

00:52.319 --> 00:53.585
Basil:
<i> I'm not getting</i>
<i> on that boat!</i>

00:53.621 --> 00:55.720
This is what happens when you
don't keep your mouth shut.

00:56.924 --> 00:59.791
Marcie:
<i> What if basil didn't</i>
<i> board that boat?</i>

00:59.860 --> 01:01.827
At some point before he's
loaded onto that boat,

01:01.962 --> 01:03.762
<i> Mike macleod and</i>
<i> his brother johnny,</i>

01:03.897 --> 01:07.065
<i> Who were hired by ned flores,</i>
<i> get into it with basil.</i>

01:07.101 --> 01:10.168
<i> According to the affidavit,</i>
<i>basil overpowered mike macleod.</i>

01:10.204 --> 01:11.303
[body thuds]

01:11.305 --> 01:13.171
[men grunting]

01:13.207 --> 01:15.507
[mike gasping]

01:18.378 --> 01:19.645
It would never
happen like that.

01:19.647 --> 01:22.046
Basil would have never gotten
the best of the macleod boys.

01:22.083 --> 01:23.048
They're vicious.

01:23.183 --> 01:24.516
We don't buy it either.

01:24.518 --> 01:26.018
<i> Those are the facts</i>
<i> that mike macleod used</i>

01:26.153 --> 01:29.187
To get the crown to agree to a
plea to criminal negligence.

01:29.189 --> 01:31.924
Marcie:
<i> Here's what we think</i>
<i> really happened.</i>

01:32.059 --> 01:36.794
<i> Mike and his brother johnny,</i>
<i> they try to intimidate basil,</i>

01:36.831 --> 01:40.132
<i> Get him to keep quiet about</i>
<i> how his brother desmond died.</i>

01:40.134 --> 01:42.868
<i> But then they threaten</i>
<i> him but basil refuses.</i>

01:43.003 --> 01:44.169
Then things escalate.

01:44.171 --> 01:49.007
[grunting]

01:49.009 --> 01:50.775
[loud crack]

01:50.811 --> 01:53.445
Doug:
<i> Then, they put his</i>
<i> body on that boat.</i>

01:53.514 --> 01:57.215
And they toss his body into
the ocean like he was nothing.

01:57.284 --> 02:00.151
Marcie:
<i> He was dead before they</i>
<i> tossed him into the atlantic.</i>

02:00.153 --> 02:01.219
Doug:
<i> But the crown doesn't</i>
<i> have enough evidence</i>

02:01.255 --> 02:02.254
To prove that theory.

02:02.256 --> 02:03.254
Marcie:
<i> But it is civil court,</i>

02:03.290 --> 02:04.656
<i> We don't need to</i>
<i> prove how he died</i>

02:04.658 --> 02:06.457
To make our claim
of wrongful death.

02:07.962 --> 02:10.428
He was under the supervision
of goldenview fields employees

02:10.498 --> 02:13.298
And he died because
of their negligence.

02:13.300 --> 02:15.367
[phone dings]

02:15.369 --> 02:16.702
Department of agriculture.

02:16.704 --> 02:17.802
They're on their way.

02:17.872 --> 02:18.836
Good.

02:18.873 --> 02:20.873
[pensive music]

02:21.008 --> 02:30.949
[indistinct jovial chatter]

02:35.923 --> 02:37.722
Hey, you made it!

02:38.826 --> 02:40.658
<i> Aww, is that for us?</i>

02:42.596 --> 02:45.731
It was, but didn't realize
you had champagne on tap.

02:45.866 --> 02:47.332
Oh, hey brother.

02:48.035 --> 02:49.133
You must be ellery.

02:49.170 --> 02:51.470
I am, you must be walt.

02:51.605 --> 02:52.871
Happy birthday!

02:52.873 --> 02:54.539
Pretty mind-blowing.

02:54.608 --> 02:56.008
Have you met my sister,
kristin?

02:56.010 --> 02:57.175
Hey.

02:57.211 --> 02:58.477
<i> Don't forget to check</i>
<i> out the bouncy castle</i>

02:58.479 --> 03:00.345
Before this big boy gets
in there and destroys it.

03:00.480 --> 03:01.613
Okay, it's not a
birthday party

03:01.615 --> 03:03.415
Unless you break your
nose in the bouncy castle.

03:03.484 --> 03:04.483
Mm-hmm.

03:04.485 --> 03:05.617
Oh, here comes boss,
heads up.

03:05.752 --> 03:07.285
<i> Kristin, do you have visine?</i>
<i> I need visine.</i>

03:07.321 --> 03:08.320
Kristin:<i> No.</i>
-Okay.

03:08.322 --> 03:09.421
Okay. Nice to meet you ellery.

03:09.490 --> 03:11.055
You too.

03:11.759 --> 03:14.192
Brian:
<i> Miss lopez.</i>

03:14.261 --> 03:15.761
Glad that you could make it.

03:15.896 --> 03:17.495
"miss lopez"?

03:17.531 --> 03:19.231
<i> It's ellery.</i>

03:19.366 --> 03:21.166
Of course.

03:21.168 --> 03:22.234
Eller-

03:22.369 --> 03:23.902
Woman:
[laughs]<i> looking good!</i>

03:23.904 --> 03:24.836
Man:
<i> Woo!</i>

03:24.905 --> 03:26.638
Ah, excuse me, I...

03:26.674 --> 03:29.041
Have to take care of this
before my mom freaks

03:29.043 --> 03:30.976
And forgets it's
his birthday.

03:31.879 --> 03:32.911
<i> Walt!</i>

03:33.046 --> 03:34.679
Are you sure this
isn't weird?

03:34.814 --> 03:36.248
Ell, chill.

03:36.383 --> 03:37.716
It's gonna be okay.

03:37.718 --> 03:39.517
[indistinct chatter]
[upbeat background music]

03:45.226 --> 03:48.393
[suspenseful music]

03:48.395 --> 03:49.394
Agent:
<i> Brian clawford,</i>

03:49.396 --> 03:51.263
<i> Agent markham</i>
<i> from agriculture.</i>

03:51.398 --> 03:52.397
<i> We received a complaint</i>

03:52.399 --> 03:53.999
<i> Concerning the treatment</i>
<i> of your workers.</i>

03:54.001 --> 03:55.000
Brian:
<i> Complaint?</i>

03:55.002 --> 03:55.867
Complaint from who?

03:55.936 --> 03:57.068
Agent:
<i> Have a look, sir.</i>

03:57.104 --> 04:03.008
[suspenseful music]

04:03.143 --> 04:15.754
♪

04:15.756 --> 04:18.556
[suspenseful music swells]

04:18.558 --> 04:21.359
Tell your boss that she's
messed with the wrong family!

04:21.495 --> 04:22.360
Get your hands off me.

04:22.396 --> 04:24.496
Brian, brian,
what are you doing?!

04:24.565 --> 04:25.763
Brian!

04:25.799 --> 04:31.769
[suspenseful music swells]

04:35.109 --> 04:36.407
Marcie:
<i> Hey dion, it's marcie diggs.</i>

04:36.443 --> 04:38.143
I'm just calling about
the trudy willis interview

04:38.145 --> 04:39.077
<i> With goldenview.</i>

04:39.146 --> 04:40.845
The raid at the clawfords?
Was that us?

04:40.914 --> 04:42.046
<i> Why wasn't I in the know?</i>

04:42.048 --> 04:43.315
Hey, we weren't trying
to leave you out.

04:43.317 --> 04:44.749
Marcie:
<i> Yeah, we knew it'd</i>
<i> be near impossible</i>

04:44.785 --> 04:46.451
For brian clawford
to avoid service

04:46.453 --> 04:47.586
At his brother's
birthday party.

04:47.721 --> 04:49.054
[phone dings]
you could have
called or texted me.

04:49.056 --> 04:51.189
Doug:
<i> We did but you</i>
<i> didn't pick up.</i>

04:51.191 --> 04:52.790
Where were you anyway?

04:54.028 --> 04:55.394
<i> It's my contact at the</i>
<i> department of agriculture.</i>

04:55.529 --> 04:58.964
He's saying investigation into
the complaint is completed.

04:59.099 --> 05:01.265
<i> They searched the bunkhouses</i>
<i> and they're up to code,</i>

05:01.302 --> 05:03.901
<i> So the clawfords and</i>
<i> goldenview fields are cleared.</i>

05:05.639 --> 05:06.872
We need iris on this.

05:07.007 --> 05:07.972
She's out sick.

05:08.008 --> 05:09.141
Doug:
<i> Still?</i>

05:09.143 --> 05:10.676
It's been over a week.

05:11.612 --> 05:13.178
Something's not right.

05:14.114 --> 05:15.947
Agriculture never
works this fast.

05:15.949 --> 05:18.916
[mysterious music]

05:22.155 --> 05:23.621
Doug:
<i> That's my nmi's recipe.</i>

05:23.757 --> 05:25.424
It's the best thing
when you're sick.

05:25.559 --> 05:29.628
I'm grateful but I'm
not that kind of sick.

05:29.630 --> 05:31.029
What you went
through with cliff,

05:31.164 --> 05:32.697
That'd be hard
on anyone.

05:32.699 --> 05:34.032
Yeah, um...

05:35.002 --> 05:36.568
I'm getting through.

05:37.471 --> 05:39.203
Well, if you need
anything, I'm...

05:41.108 --> 05:42.707
I'm busy like hell
with work and wedding,

05:42.710 --> 05:44.275
But I'm here for you.

05:45.045 --> 05:46.311
How's marcie?

05:46.313 --> 05:47.812
Back to her old self.

05:48.982 --> 05:50.882
<i> I really hope you can</i>
<i> make it to the wedding.</i>

05:55.089 --> 05:56.588
You deserve good things,
iris.

05:59.827 --> 06:01.193
Marcie:
<i> I know that our</i>
<i> initial agreement</i>

06:01.328 --> 06:03.395
Didn't include a
payment plan but-

06:03.397 --> 06:06.130
I don't do layaway,
marcie.

06:07.401 --> 06:10.001
<i> Firm's been making all</i>
<i> those giant contingency fees</i>

06:10.003 --> 06:10.935
On those settlements-

06:11.070 --> 06:12.370
Settlements
reduced on appeal-

06:12.373 --> 06:14.339
Look, you were
very clear

06:14.408 --> 06:16.774
That our arrangement
wasn't working for you.

06:19.846 --> 06:21.546
[softly] I don't have
eight million dollars.

06:22.816 --> 06:25.016
[softly] seems like
a "you" problem.

06:25.018 --> 06:26.617
Waitress:
<i> Are you ready to order?</i>

06:27.888 --> 06:30.388
<i> We'll start with a bottle</i>
<i> of the antinori tignanello,</i>

06:30.391 --> 06:32.757
Some carpaccio and
bread for the table.

06:32.760 --> 06:34.358
Waitress:
<i> Coming right up.</i>

06:35.195 --> 06:36.027
Vivian:
<i> Seriously though,</i>

06:36.029 --> 06:37.762
I'm sure your
winning track record

06:37.798 --> 06:39.764
Will attract
some suitors.

06:39.767 --> 06:43.100
In fact,
you know ezra.

06:43.137 --> 06:44.870
Well, well, well!

06:45.005 --> 06:46.371
Hi marcie.

06:49.276 --> 06:52.109
Vivian:
<i> I understand ezra's been a</i>
<i> long time fan of your work.</i>

06:52.146 --> 06:54.145
I've always
admired how marcie

06:54.214 --> 06:56.447
Will do anything
for the win.

06:56.483 --> 06:59.251
[chuckles]

06:59.253 --> 07:02.987
[suspenseful music]

07:03.056 --> 07:05.123
She needs to know howard
is doing shady things

07:05.125 --> 07:06.090
Behind her back.

07:06.160 --> 07:09.327
Emily told us they have
their arrangement.

07:09.396 --> 07:10.328
Hmm.

07:10.397 --> 07:11.663
Let it be, austin.

07:11.732 --> 07:12.864
Emily:
<i> Mom, dad!</i>

07:12.999 --> 07:14.132
Ah!

07:14.201 --> 07:15.733
Emily:
<i> What's up?</i>

07:15.769 --> 07:17.335
Oh, this is robin.

07:19.139 --> 07:20.738
Ah.
-Ah.

07:22.910 --> 07:24.242
They double booked the hall.

07:24.378 --> 07:26.110
Didn't we already
give them a deposit?

07:27.414 --> 07:29.814
They said there's
an emergency
council meeting.

07:31.918 --> 07:33.385
We'll talk to melanie.

07:33.520 --> 07:35.420
She took over as chief after
your father, didn't she?

07:35.555 --> 07:37.955
Her voicemail says she's
still out of the country.

07:39.192 --> 07:40.558
Is this a sign?

07:40.594 --> 07:42.193
I mean, what do we
need a wedding for?

07:42.196 --> 07:43.160
<i> We're good, right?</i>

07:43.197 --> 07:45.030
Chell, our wedding
is gonna be

07:45.165 --> 07:46.364
The celebration
that you deserve,

07:46.366 --> 07:48.900
Even if we have to have it
in a quick-stop parking lot.

07:49.035 --> 07:50.035
<i> Okay?</i>

07:50.037 --> 07:51.469
Mm-hmm.

07:52.206 --> 07:53.805
Oh, sorry to interrupt.

07:54.942 --> 07:57.042
We've been asked to go
to the clawford estate

07:57.177 --> 07:58.643
For a settlement
conference.

07:58.645 --> 08:00.378
Michelle:
<i> Isn't it a three</i>
<i> hour drive to pei?</i>

08:00.514 --> 08:03.114
Oh, we won't be driving.

08:03.250 --> 08:06.718
[swanky music]

08:06.787 --> 08:08.186
Ellery:
<i> This is a flex!</i>

08:08.188 --> 08:10.454
Hey, make sure you send me
a draft of that argument

08:10.491 --> 08:12.123
<i> So I can take a look at it.</i>

08:12.125 --> 08:14.259
<i> I'll see you at the</i>
<i> publication ban at four.</i>

08:14.261 --> 08:20.098
[swanky music swells]

08:20.167 --> 08:24.135
♪

08:25.873 --> 08:28.540
Brian:
<i> My sister likes to cosplay</i>
<i> as one of the people.</i>

08:28.675 --> 08:30.041
Kristin:
<i> I don't ask the</i>
<i> workers to do anything</i>

08:30.043 --> 08:31.142
I'm not willing
to do myself.

08:31.211 --> 08:32.978
Marcie:
<i> You know how to</i>
<i> operate a combine?</i>

08:32.980 --> 08:33.945
In my sleep.

08:33.981 --> 08:35.846
And live fifteen
to a bunkhouse

08:35.883 --> 08:37.282
Earning minimum wage

08:37.284 --> 08:39.250
And doing back
breaking work?

08:40.654 --> 08:41.919
You're clever.

08:41.955 --> 08:44.956
Brian:
<i> What my sister is</i>
<i> trying to say, badly,</i>

08:45.025 --> 08:47.492
Is that we care
for our workers.

08:47.494 --> 08:49.226
Tragic accidents like
what happened to basil-

08:49.263 --> 08:50.995
It wasn't an accident.

08:51.031 --> 08:53.498
One of your employees
killed basil.

08:53.567 --> 08:54.832
He confessed.

08:54.868 --> 08:56.834
Flame:
<i> We're prepared to offer</i>
<i> a large settlement</i>

08:56.870 --> 08:59.371
Of $75,000 to ms. Willis.

08:59.373 --> 09:02.840
Well, any offer needs to
include the implementation

09:02.876 --> 09:04.508
Of new safety measures,

09:04.645 --> 09:05.743
<i> In line with</i>
<i> the guidelines</i>

09:05.812 --> 09:07.779
<i> Set by the migrant</i>
<i> workers association.</i>

09:07.914 --> 09:09.180
Otherwise there's
really no deal here.

09:09.216 --> 09:11.282
Kristin:
<i> We understand that the</i>
<i> work that we do here</i>

09:11.351 --> 09:12.683
Is physically taxing

09:12.719 --> 09:15.119
And yes, dangerous.

09:15.155 --> 09:17.722
Hell, I almost lost a
hand the other day.

09:17.758 --> 09:19.057
<i> We run a good</i>
<i> operation here.</i>

09:19.059 --> 09:20.925
Doug:
<i> But two brothers who</i>
<i> are your employees</i>

09:20.994 --> 09:22.560
Died under your care.

09:23.397 --> 09:24.395
Where's the
accountability?

09:24.397 --> 09:26.264
I think what my siblings
are trying to say

09:26.333 --> 09:29.534
Is that this was truly
an honest tragedy.

09:29.536 --> 09:31.603
We wanna pay restitution
for any small part

09:31.672 --> 09:32.804
We may have played.

09:32.939 --> 09:35.039
Brian:
<i> And our offer reflects</i>
<i> what we believe</i>

09:35.075 --> 09:36.741
Our degree of
culpability to be.

09:36.876 --> 09:37.875
Hmm.

09:37.945 --> 09:39.844
Brian:
<i> If you take it</i>
<i> to your client,</i>

09:39.846 --> 09:41.646
<i> I'm sure she'll</i>
<i> find it suitable.</i>

09:41.781 --> 09:43.949
It is a lot of money.

09:44.084 --> 09:47.652
Marcie:
<i> You're offering $75,000</i>
<i> for a man's life?</i>

09:48.755 --> 09:53.357
All of his hopes and his
aspirations, $75,000.

09:53.393 --> 09:54.826
Wow.

09:56.096 --> 09:58.562
<i> You know, by my estimate,</i>
<i> goldenview's ability</i>

09:58.599 --> 10:01.966
To access the government's
temporary workers program,

10:02.002 --> 10:04.836
That results in at least
sixty million dollars

10:04.971 --> 10:06.104
To your bottom line.

10:06.106 --> 10:08.239
I don't know where you're
getting your numbers from.

10:08.375 --> 10:10.375
My point, brian,

10:10.444 --> 10:11.910
Is if you're banned
from the program,

10:12.045 --> 10:13.911
Then you're screwed.

10:13.947 --> 10:18.983
[suspenseful music]

10:18.986 --> 10:20.518
I think we're done here.

10:23.023 --> 10:24.588
You're making a big mistake.

10:25.659 --> 10:27.992
Not as costly as the
one you're making.

10:28.061 --> 10:33.798
[tense dramatic music]

10:33.800 --> 10:46.777
♪

10:49.349 --> 10:51.149
Ng]

10:51.151 --> 10:53.818
Well, it's not exactly
fin du monde,

10:53.820 --> 10:56.420
<i> But they make a pretty</i>
<i> decent craft beer here.</i>

10:56.456 --> 10:58.156
<i> You sure you don't want one?</i>

10:58.158 --> 11:00.291
No, I've got court in
a couple of hours.

11:00.360 --> 11:01.292
Goldenview?

11:01.361 --> 11:02.627
Yeah.

11:02.696 --> 11:04.095
They're trying to...

11:04.131 --> 11:07.165
Do a complete publication
ban surrounding our case.

11:07.167 --> 11:08.767
Ah, well.

11:08.769 --> 11:09.967
Okay, we better get to it.

11:10.003 --> 11:13.838
Um, professional
misconduct hearing is

11:13.973 --> 11:15.273
More a nuisance
than anything

11:15.275 --> 11:17.609
But reputationally
it can get ugly.

11:17.744 --> 11:19.577
We're gonna go in there
and make our case-

11:19.646 --> 11:21.179
But reg, am I gonna
get disbarred?

11:21.181 --> 11:23.781
No, I mean, they'll
make you take a course,

11:23.850 --> 11:25.583
Pay a fine.

11:25.585 --> 11:28.787
But it depends on what their
investigators come up with

11:29.856 --> 11:31.923
And who else comes
outta the woodwork.

11:32.058 --> 11:33.324
This bloody judge.

11:33.326 --> 11:34.859
You know, dewey's
only going after me

11:34.861 --> 11:36.794
Because she wants to
get back at colleen.

11:36.930 --> 11:41.866
She's a petty,
petty person.

11:41.902 --> 11:43.801
Speaking of petty people.

11:43.837 --> 11:44.836
How's viv?

11:44.838 --> 11:46.303
Marcie:
<i> Ugh.</i>

11:47.240 --> 11:49.274
Well she's frozen
our line of credit

11:49.409 --> 11:51.776
And she's planning on selling
her stake of the firm

11:51.912 --> 11:53.411
To ezra elvins.

11:53.480 --> 11:55.012
[reg laughs]

11:55.014 --> 11:56.214
Well, you gotta
hand it to her.

11:56.349 --> 11:57.949
She knows how to
wield a knife!

11:58.018 --> 11:59.150
Yeah.

11:59.219 --> 12:00.284
You got a plan?

12:00.320 --> 12:02.087
Find eight million dollars.

12:02.222 --> 12:04.556
Look, I-I know it's gonna
sound funny coming from me

12:04.691 --> 12:08.459
But maybe you should take
another crack at viv.

12:08.495 --> 12:10.828
Appeal to the side
of ms. Jefferson

12:10.864 --> 12:13.063
That made her back ya
in the first place.

12:16.036 --> 12:17.501
[phone vibrates]

12:19.706 --> 12:20.638
Trudy, what's up?

12:20.774 --> 12:22.373
Jean just called me.

12:22.442 --> 12:23.441
Basil's mom.

12:23.443 --> 12:25.076
What did she say?

12:25.078 --> 12:27.578
Trudy:
<i> She said cruz called her,</i>
<i> told her about the lawsuit.</i>

12:27.614 --> 12:30.348
Said I was trying to make
money off of basil's death.

12:30.483 --> 12:32.583
Okay, trudy, I need
you to calm down.

12:32.718 --> 12:34.519
She's on her way here, marcie.

12:34.654 --> 12:36.621
She's gonna help them
stop our lawsuit.

12:36.623 --> 12:38.656
Did she tell you what
flight she'd be on?

12:40.761 --> 12:42.193
Okay.

12:43.463 --> 12:44.996
What's going on?

12:46.332 --> 12:47.599
[marcie sighs]

12:47.601 --> 12:49.334
Just running a play.

12:49.469 --> 12:51.135
[phone keys clacking]

12:53.607 --> 12:56.407
I was looking forward to
introducing you to my parents.

12:56.443 --> 12:58.743
Marcie doesn't
know about us.

12:58.878 --> 13:00.278
Whatever "us" is.

13:00.347 --> 13:02.279
And everything
is escalating

13:02.315 --> 13:04.715
And you and I have
already crossed a line.

13:04.751 --> 13:06.050
Tell me about it.

13:06.052 --> 13:07.886
No, this isn't funny,
this is not good.

13:08.021 --> 13:09.788
I don't care.

13:09.923 --> 13:11.455
I'm not my family.

13:12.458 --> 13:13.958
Your brother lays a
hand on me again,

13:13.960 --> 13:16.027
I'm gonna kick the
shit out of him.

13:16.096 --> 13:17.695
I'll buy tickets to that.

13:20.901 --> 13:22.633
Andrea, when our
civil case is over,

13:22.669 --> 13:25.236
We're gonna hand all of
our evidence to the crown.

13:25.272 --> 13:28.173
Your brother is looking
at some serious charges.

13:28.308 --> 13:30.909
Conspiracy to commit murder,
accessory after the fact.

13:30.911 --> 13:32.476
<i> Stop, stop.</i>

13:33.513 --> 13:34.512
You're trying to put
my brother in jail?

13:34.647 --> 13:36.147
If it's warranted.

13:37.050 --> 13:38.849
We'll never let
you do that.

13:38.885 --> 13:42.853
[soft background music]

13:44.357 --> 13:45.823
Melanie?

13:47.494 --> 13:49.060
I'll see you.

13:50.463 --> 13:51.396
Doug:
<i> Melanie, I thought you</i>
<i> were out of the country.</i>

13:51.531 --> 13:52.997
Plans changed.

13:53.066 --> 13:55.799
Oh, great, so you're
coming to the wedding.

13:55.836 --> 13:57.335
I don't know about all that.

13:57.470 --> 13:58.736
<i> We all caught the original.</i>

13:58.871 --> 13:59.904
No one wants a remake.

13:59.906 --> 14:00.839
We want this, mel.

14:00.974 --> 14:04.008
It's embarrassing for
the community, doug.

14:04.143 --> 14:05.409
<i> I've been married, divorced,</i>

14:05.478 --> 14:07.945
<i> Remarried, divorced</i>
<i> again in twenty years,</i>

14:07.981 --> 14:09.881
And still people
whisper and snicker

14:10.016 --> 14:12.350
Every time my name comes up
with yours and michelle's.

14:12.352 --> 14:13.417
<i> It's not a good look.</i>

14:13.453 --> 14:15.486
So that's the cause of
this "emergency meeting"?

14:15.488 --> 14:18.522
Melanie:
<i> The community is tired of</i>
<i> dealing with our trauma.</i>

14:20.360 --> 14:21.926
I have to go.

14:28.601 --> 14:29.968
Oh.

14:31.304 --> 14:33.304
[chuckles]

14:33.439 --> 14:35.173
Well, now that we're
all reacquainted,

14:35.175 --> 14:36.541
To the airport.

14:36.543 --> 14:39.176
Ah, ma'am, I've been instructed
to drive you back to halifax.

14:39.178 --> 14:41.312
Well we were told that
we were taking the jet.

14:41.314 --> 14:42.847
The jet's no
longer available.

14:44.050 --> 14:47.018
We're never gonna make the
publication ban hearing.

14:47.087 --> 14:48.419
They screwed us.

14:48.554 --> 14:53.992
[tense dramatic music]

14:53.994 --> 14:55.059
Marcie:
<i> Ellery,</i>

14:55.194 --> 14:56.460
What happened in there?

14:56.529 --> 14:58.596
They granted the clawford's
request for a publication ban-

14:58.731 --> 14:59.930
The judge spouted
some garbage

14:59.966 --> 15:01.466
About goldenview's
fortunes being tied

15:01.601 --> 15:02.800
<i> To the provincial economy.</i>

15:02.836 --> 15:04.001
Well that reasoning
won't stand.

15:04.137 --> 15:05.135
Dion:
<i> Already filed the appeal.</i>

15:05.171 --> 15:06.637
We'll catch up for the
interview with trudy

15:06.673 --> 15:08.239
<i> After this mess is done.</i>

15:13.546 --> 15:15.212
[sighs]

15:15.248 --> 15:17.047
All there ever is
is junk anyway.

15:18.118 --> 15:20.150
Well it's about time
you had that junk

15:20.186 --> 15:22.386
Redirected to
your new address.

15:24.223 --> 15:26.925
You didn't get that
done up for bible study.

15:27.060 --> 15:28.626
<i> Who's the lucky man?</i>

15:28.761 --> 15:30.261
It's none of your business.

15:31.765 --> 15:34.031
You going out to
dinner with emily?

15:34.167 --> 15:35.633
Of course I am.

15:37.304 --> 15:39.771
It doesn't bother you?
The way she's living?

15:40.707 --> 15:42.373
What about the
way she's living?

15:42.508 --> 15:46.143
Seems like everybody
knows where they stand.

15:46.145 --> 15:48.379
Everything's out in the open.

15:48.415 --> 15:51.549
But it's really none
of your business.

15:51.618 --> 15:53.651
What about the kids?

15:53.720 --> 15:56.120
What are they learning
about commitment?

15:56.255 --> 15:57.188
[scoffs] don't go there, austin.

15:57.323 --> 16:00.057
I see emily making the
same mistakes I made.

16:01.194 --> 16:02.192
I just want better for her.

16:02.228 --> 16:04.595
But she's not making
your mistakes.

16:04.597 --> 16:07.732
There's no lying,
no hiding.

16:07.734 --> 16:09.534
<i> They trust each other.</i>

16:09.669 --> 16:11.536
Emily and howard,

16:11.538 --> 16:13.471
All the cards are
on the table.

16:15.008 --> 16:16.940
Million ways to
make an apple pie.

16:18.011 --> 16:21.879
May not be your way
but it's still good.

16:24.517 --> 16:26.484
Marcie:
<i> How can you say she</i>
<i> has no standing?!</i>

16:26.619 --> 16:27.951
They were as good
as common-law!

16:27.988 --> 16:29.354
But they weren't.

16:29.489 --> 16:30.988
<i> They weren't living together,</i>
<i> they weren't getting married.</i>

16:30.991 --> 16:34.225
<i> What harm is she suffering</i>
<i> because of mr. Allen's death?</i>

16:34.360 --> 16:36.126
They weren't living
together because basil

16:36.162 --> 16:38.196
Had to stay at the
goldenview bunkhouses.

16:38.331 --> 16:39.397
There are plenty
of married couples

16:39.532 --> 16:40.431
<i> Who don't even</i>
<i> live together.</i>

16:40.566 --> 16:42.933
What it comes down
to is companionship,

16:42.969 --> 16:44.836
Emotional support
and love.

16:44.838 --> 16:46.303
Enough!

16:47.440 --> 16:50.575
I'm open to taking a less
restrictive definition

16:50.710 --> 16:53.310
Of standing in
wrongful death cases.

16:53.380 --> 16:56.047
<i> If I see that</i>
<i> she has grounds,</i>

16:56.049 --> 16:58.749
Then I will permit this
case to go to trial.

17:00.353 --> 17:07.758
[soft dramatic music]

17:19.773 --> 17:21.605
Thought we concluded
our business, marcie.

17:21.641 --> 17:23.741
Ezra elvins is
not a solution.

17:23.876 --> 17:25.409
Solves my problem.

17:26.780 --> 17:28.613
I'm sorry about how
you left the office-

17:28.748 --> 17:30.781
Vivian:
<i> An apology?</i>

17:30.817 --> 17:32.316
You must be desperate.

17:33.786 --> 17:36.154
Can't we just find a way to
move beyond this together?

17:36.156 --> 17:38.289
Vivian:
<i> You were my pay forward.</i>

17:38.291 --> 17:40.124
Then you turned around
and treated my generosity

17:40.259 --> 17:42.626
Like it was a
rock in your shoe.

17:43.763 --> 17:45.362
<i> Acting like I was a bother.</i>

17:45.398 --> 17:46.964
Pain in the ass.

17:47.967 --> 17:50.033
Look, I'm extremely grateful-

17:50.070 --> 17:51.602
You were the opposite.

17:52.772 --> 17:54.505
Now you need me
to be reasonable,

17:55.442 --> 17:58.142
<i> To be fair,</i>
<i> to be a sista'.</i>

17:59.979 --> 18:01.512
You don't deserve me.

18:01.647 --> 18:09.353
[suspenseful music]

18:12.392 --> 18:16.260
Percy, thank you for picking
up jean from the airport.

18:16.262 --> 18:18.128
Well, she needed
some convincing.

18:18.164 --> 18:19.263
You know, that was

18:19.265 --> 18:22.166
A pretty smooth limo the
clawfords sent for her.

18:22.168 --> 18:23.668
Let's get her to the office.

18:23.670 --> 18:25.068
Hold on, marcie.

18:25.105 --> 18:29.339
[pensive music]

18:29.375 --> 18:30.541
No, no, no, no,
don't do this.

18:30.677 --> 18:32.509
You and these
clawford people,

18:33.580 --> 18:35.146
You're having a
street fight.

18:36.182 --> 18:38.149
Jean allen is a
grieving mother,

18:38.218 --> 18:40.151
<i> Not some pawn.</i>

18:40.153 --> 18:42.687
Someone needs to
be in her corner,

18:42.822 --> 18:44.488
Give her cover.

18:44.491 --> 18:45.622
And that's going to be me.

18:45.658 --> 18:47.325
Percy, do not do this.

18:47.460 --> 18:50.227
Oh, we gotta do what we do,

18:50.263 --> 18:51.762
You know that.

18:53.500 --> 18:54.532
I'll catch you later.

18:54.601 --> 19:01.372
[tense dramatic music]

19:04.711 --> 19:06.644
Once basil got
his citizenship,

19:07.814 --> 19:10.047
We were gonna open
a restaurant.

19:10.116 --> 19:12.650
<i> Now I spend most days</i>
<i> explaining to my boys</i>

19:12.652 --> 19:14.451
<i> Why basil's not</i>
<i> coming back.</i>

19:16.089 --> 19:17.788
Sounds like basil played a,

19:17.824 --> 19:20.258
A special role in
your sons' lives.

19:21.161 --> 19:23.393
He was the father
they needed.

19:23.429 --> 19:24.595
Were you married?

19:24.730 --> 19:26.330
Trudy:
<i> We looked at it.</i>

19:26.332 --> 19:28.499
<i> But legally,</i>
<i> I'm already married.</i>

19:28.634 --> 19:30.101
My ex and I,
we just,

19:31.171 --> 19:33.070
We couldn't afford a divorce.

19:33.206 --> 19:36.273
Marcie:
<i> What was your impression</i>
<i> of his workplace?</i>

19:37.810 --> 19:42.112
He was unhappy about
the working conditions.

19:43.482 --> 19:46.550
<i> How untrained people were</i>
<i> operating heavy machinery.</i>

19:46.553 --> 19:48.486
<i> The conditions of</i>
<i> the living quarters.</i>

19:48.488 --> 19:50.288
They once had an
infestation of bed bugs

19:50.423 --> 19:52.823
So bad they had to
torch the bunkhouse.

19:54.594 --> 19:57.194
Marcie:
<i> And to your knowledge,</i>
<i> did he do anything about it?</i>

19:57.263 --> 19:58.696
Trudy:
<i> Not at first.</i>

19:58.765 --> 20:03.000
He was afraid if he said
anything he'd get sent home.

20:04.103 --> 20:06.637
<i> But after his little</i>
<i> brother desmond died</i>

20:06.772 --> 20:08.505
<i> While working on the farm,</i>

20:10.276 --> 20:12.042
Basil believed goldenview,

20:13.079 --> 20:14.711
The clawfords
were responsible.

20:16.515 --> 20:18.048
<i> And now he's dead.</i>

20:18.918 --> 20:20.517
Killed by one of
their people.

20:23.456 --> 20:24.989
Thank you.

20:27.293 --> 20:29.660
Ms. Willis, let's talk
about this restaurant

20:29.662 --> 20:31.795
<i> That you and the deceased</i>
<i> intended to open.</i>

20:31.831 --> 20:33.130
Did you have a location?

20:33.266 --> 20:34.464
No.

20:34.500 --> 20:36.366
Did you have a real estate
agent looking for a location?

20:36.402 --> 20:37.568
No.

20:37.637 --> 20:39.169
Isn't it true that your plans
to open this restaurant

20:39.239 --> 20:41.071
With the late mr. Allen
began and ended

20:41.107 --> 20:42.139
With a google search?

20:42.175 --> 20:44.207
We were just
starting the process

20:44.244 --> 20:46.143
Before your clients
had him killed.

20:46.179 --> 20:47.244
Your honour...

20:47.313 --> 20:49.947
Just answer the questions,
ms. Willis.

20:49.949 --> 20:51.649
Flame:
<i> Ms. Willis, please</i>
<i> read the first page</i>

20:51.784 --> 20:53.317
Of defence exhibit 22.

21:02.662 --> 21:04.561
"liz, I wanna
get married too.

21:04.597 --> 21:06.897
"if I'm lucky,
maybe it can be with you."

21:09.402 --> 21:12.469
Flame:
<i> Who's the liz that basil's</i>
<i> addressing in this message?</i>

21:13.272 --> 21:14.171
No idea.

21:14.240 --> 21:15.172
'cause he was
cheating on you?

21:15.241 --> 21:16.507
No, he wasn't!

21:16.509 --> 21:17.641
Flame:
<i> He was never gonna marry you,</i>
<i> was he?</i>

21:17.677 --> 21:19.844
<i> He was never gonna open</i>
<i> a restaurant with you.</i>

21:19.979 --> 21:22.412
This lawsuit is just
about the money, isn't it?

21:22.448 --> 21:24.115
Objection! Argumentative!

21:24.117 --> 21:25.716
Mr. Macdonald,

21:25.851 --> 21:29.586
<i> Do you know what it's like</i>
<i> to spend your whole life</i>

21:29.656 --> 21:31.789
Never expecting
anyone to see you?

21:31.858 --> 21:33.457
[stammers] who gets your mess?

21:34.527 --> 21:36.593
I found that with basil.
We found that.

21:36.629 --> 21:39.063
Isn't someone responsible
for taking that from me?

21:39.198 --> 21:40.797
From my boys?

21:40.799 --> 21:42.432
Shouldn't someone
have to pay?

21:42.468 --> 21:48.406
[pensive music]

21:48.408 --> 21:50.240
Flame:
<i> I'm done, your honour.</i>

21:53.813 --> 21:55.880
Cruz:
<i> Basil blamed the</i>
<i> clawfords for the death</i>

21:56.015 --> 21:58.349
<i> Of his little brother,</i>
<i> desmond.</i>

21:58.351 --> 22:01.017
We were good
friends until then.

22:01.154 --> 22:02.286
What changed?

22:02.421 --> 22:05.021
Cruz:
<i> He was going to complain</i>
<i> to the government.</i>

22:05.058 --> 22:07.191
Ellery:
<i> Yes, basil allen did</i>
<i> intend to go public</i>

22:07.193 --> 22:08.825
With the working
conditions on the farm.

22:08.861 --> 22:10.761
In fact, 48 hours
before he died,

22:10.896 --> 22:11.828
The two of you argued.

22:11.864 --> 22:12.963
You fought about this.

22:12.965 --> 22:15.165
He was going to ruin
it for everybody.

22:15.234 --> 22:18.302
<i> I know desmond's death was</i>
<i> just a tragic accident.</i>

22:19.906 --> 22:22.573
But basil wouldn't shut up.

22:22.642 --> 22:24.975
He wouldn't leave it alone.

22:25.111 --> 22:26.444
And after your fight,

22:26.579 --> 22:28.979
Basil allen was put on a
truck for parts unknown

22:29.048 --> 22:31.615
Where he was then killed
by michael macleod.

22:31.617 --> 22:33.584
<i> Do you know mr. Macleod?</i>

22:33.586 --> 22:36.553
He was, um, he was
one of ned's guys.

22:38.324 --> 22:40.323
By "one of ned's guys"
you mean ned flores,

22:40.360 --> 22:41.392
The grounds manager

22:41.394 --> 22:43.661
Of goldenview's
nova scotia operation?

22:43.796 --> 22:45.195
Yes.

22:46.366 --> 22:47.864
Thank you.

22:49.202 --> 22:51.034
Oh, one more question.

22:52.104 --> 22:54.071
Do you still work for
goldenview fields?

22:56.075 --> 23:00.611
I am the clawford's personal
groundskeeper in pei.

23:00.746 --> 23:03.547
[pensive music]

23:03.583 --> 23:04.748
So you get a promotion

23:04.751 --> 23:06.951
And your friend gets
tossed into the atlantic.

23:07.086 --> 23:13.958
[suspenseful music]

23:14.093 --> 23:21.865
♪

23:27.373 --> 23:28.839
Um...

23:28.974 --> 23:30.374
Can we help you?

23:30.376 --> 23:31.842
Cruz:
<i> Mrs. Allen,</i>

23:33.179 --> 23:34.978
<i> Your sons</i>
<i> desmond and basil,</i>

23:35.014 --> 23:37.014
They were good men.

23:37.149 --> 23:40.718
Basil, he...He truly
cared for family.

23:40.853 --> 23:41.986
<i> He would often</i>
<i> speak about you-</i>

23:41.988 --> 23:43.354
[sharp slap]
[pained grunt]

23:43.489 --> 23:47.524
[tense dramatic music]

23:47.560 --> 23:50.594
[soft sobbing]

23:50.596 --> 23:51.996
Are you okay?

23:52.131 --> 23:53.563
Yeah.

23:54.734 --> 23:55.666
Darcy:
<i> Shouldn't be</i>
<i> surprised to find you</i>

23:55.735 --> 23:57.901
<i> With your head</i>
<i> buried in work.</i>

23:57.970 --> 23:59.937
Do you ever take a break?

23:59.939 --> 24:01.905
Well, you of all
people know that I do.

24:05.545 --> 24:07.010
Everything all right?

24:07.046 --> 24:09.313
Darcy:
<i>I'm not sure I should go to your</i>
<i> friend's wedding with you.</i>

24:11.184 --> 24:13.217
Oh! Oh, okay.

24:13.286 --> 24:15.385
Darcy:
<i> Listen, I'm the</i>
<i> youngest chief justice</i>

24:15.455 --> 24:18.088
Of any provincial
supreme court in this country.

24:19.692 --> 24:21.791
I've worked my guts
out for this, I just...

24:23.362 --> 24:25.896
How would it look if we
were together at a wedding?

24:27.099 --> 24:30.367
It would look like two
colleagues getting together-

24:30.503 --> 24:32.435
No, it wouldn't.

24:34.040 --> 24:37.807
<i> I am interested but this</i>
<i> feels a little too fast.</i>

24:39.312 --> 24:40.911
You're right.

24:41.046 --> 24:42.646
I don't wanna hide.

24:42.682 --> 24:44.248
<i> We're not teenagers.</i>

24:45.051 --> 24:46.583
<i> I'm into you.</i>

24:47.820 --> 24:49.353
I'll go to the
wedding single.

24:51.190 --> 24:53.057
I thought you'd understand.

24:53.192 --> 25:00.997
[pensive music]

25:01.033 --> 25:02.632
[colleen sighs]

25:05.371 --> 25:07.604
Thanks for coming,
I know that you're busy.

25:08.941 --> 25:10.674
Michelle's not
taking my calls.

25:11.611 --> 25:13.310
<i> Figured we should talk.</i>

25:13.346 --> 25:15.011
I wanna make this right.

25:15.047 --> 25:17.547
<i> For you and for chell.</i>

25:17.549 --> 25:19.950
I love your sister and
I want her to be happy

25:20.085 --> 25:21.551
And I know the
way to do that

25:21.587 --> 25:23.153
Is to let her have the
wedding she'd been planning.

25:23.288 --> 25:24.922
That's what you
said last time.

25:25.057 --> 25:26.957
Look how your "love"
worked out for us.

25:27.092 --> 25:28.759
I love michelle.

25:28.761 --> 25:29.760
You've gotta trust that.

25:29.895 --> 25:31.227
Do I?

25:31.264 --> 25:35.165
Doug I knew was in love
every five minutes.

25:35.167 --> 25:38.669
We're not the same kids
